			<notes/>
			<notesNormalized/>
			<notesHtml/>
			<text>Ethical motivation: deciding what one actually wishes and intends to do.
Having identified the morally ideal course of action, putting that into place still requires the motivation to do so. Issues such as fear of negative reprisals, uncertainty about the effect we could have or concern about upsetting colleagues may deter or dissuade us from acting ethically. Similarly, having a clear sense of how we can support the people concerned or a strong ethical value-base that we always strive to adhere to may increase our motivation to act in the chosen manner. 
 
